import SiteLayout from "../../../layouts/SiteLayout.astro";

const schema = [
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "Article",
    "headline": "What is Dividend Yield? Explained with Examples",
    "description": "Learn how dividend yield is calculated, why high yields can be a trap, and the difference between dividend yield and dividend growth.",
    "url": "https://westmountfundamentals.com/what-is-dividend-yield"
  },
  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How is dividend yield calculated?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Dividend yield is calculated by dividing the annual dividend per share by the current share price, then multiplying by 100 to get a percentage."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a dividend yield trap?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A dividend trap occurs when a company's dividend yield appears artificially high because its stock price has plummeted due to underlying financial problems, often leading to an eventual dividend cut."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Is a higher dividend yield always better?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "No. Extremely high yields often indicate market skepticism that the dividend is sustainable. A moderate, growing dividend is generally safer than an exceptionally high, stagnant one."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
];
---
<SiteLayout
  site="westmount"
  title="What is Dividend Yield? The Complete Guide"
  description="Discover how dividend yield is calculated, the danger of high-yield traps, and how it compares to dividend growth investing strategies."
  canonical="https://westmountfundamentals.com/what-is-dividend-yield"
  schema={schema}
>
  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero">
      <h1>What is Dividend Yield?</h1>
      <p>Understanding Calculations, High-Yield Traps, and Growth Strategies.</p>
    </div>

    <section class="intro-section">
      <p>Dividend yield is a financial ratio that shows how much a company pays out in dividends each year relative to its stock price. It's one of the most widely used metrics by income investors seeking cash flow from their portfolios without having to sell their shares.</p>
      <p>Whether you are building a passive income stream for retirement or just starting your journey by exploring the <a href="/investing-glossary">Investing Glossary</a>, understanding dividend yield is crucial for long-term success.</p>
    </section>

    <h2>How is Dividend Yield Calculated?</h2>
    <p>The calculation for dividend yield is straightforward:</p>
    <div class="card" style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.2rem; font-weight: bold; padding: 2rem;">
      Dividend Yield = (Annual Dividend Per Share / Current Stock Price) × 100
    </div>
    <p><strong>Example:</strong> If Company ABC pays an annual dividend of $2.00 per share and its stock is currently trading at $50.00 per share, the dividend yield would be 4.0%.</p>
    <p>Because the stock price is in the denominator, the dividend yield moves inversely to the stock price. If Company ABC's stock price rises to $100 while the dividend remains $2.00, the yield drops to 2.0%. Conversely, if the stock price falls to $25, the yield spikes to 8.0%.</p>

    <h3>Trailing vs. Forward Dividend Yield</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Trailing Yield:</strong> Looks backward at the total dividends paid over the past 12 months. This is concrete historical data but may not reflect future payouts.</li>
      <li><strong>Forward Yield:</strong> Looks ahead by taking the most recent dividend payment and annualizing it. If a company just raised its quarterly dividend from $0.50 to $0.60, the forward yield uses $2.40 ($0.60 x 4) as the annual figure.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The High-Yield Trap</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <p>One of the biggest mistakes novice investors make is chasing the highest possible yield. An exceptionally high dividend yield (e.g., 8%, 10%, or 12%) is often a red flag, commonly referred to as a "dividend trap" or "value trap."</p>
      <p>Why does this happen? Remember the formula. A yield usually spikes because the stock price has plummeted. The market often aggressively sells off a stock if the company is facing severe fundamental issues, such as declining earnings or massive debt. The high yield is the market's way of demanding a massive risk premium.</p>
      <p>When you buy a dividend trap, you risk suffering a double blow: the stock price continues to fall, and the company eventually slashes or suspends the dividend entirely to conserve cash.</p>
    </div>

    <h2>Dividend Yield vs. Dividend Growth</h2>
    <p>When constructing an income portfolio, investors generally choose between two distinct strategies:</p>

    <h3>High Current Yield</h3>
    <p>This strategy focuses on stocks that offer a high current yield (e.g., 4% to 6%) right now. These are typically mature, slower-growing companies in sectors like utilities, telecommunications, or real estate (REITs). They pay out a large portion of their earnings as dividends because they have fewer high-return opportunities to reinvest the cash back into the business.</p>

    <h3>Dividend Growth</h3>
    <p>This strategy focuses on companies with a lower starting yield (e.g., 1% to 2.5%) but a history of rapidly increasing their dividend payouts year after year. These companies retain more earnings to fuel business growth, which in turn drives higher earnings and larger future dividends.</p>
    <p>Over a long time horizon, a fast-growing 2% yielder will often generate more total cash flow than a stagnant 5% yielder, due to the power of compounding. This strategy also benefits from a concept known as "Yield on Cost" (YOC), where your effective yield on your original investment grows significantly over decades.</p>

    <h2>Evaluating Dividend Safety</h2>
    <p>To avoid dividend traps and ensure your income is sustainable, you must look beyond the yield itself. The most important metric for dividend safety is the <strong>Payout Ratio</strong>.</p>
    <p>The Payout Ratio tells you what percentage of a company's earnings (or free cash flow) is being paid out as dividends. A ratio of 40% to 60% is generally considered healthy, leaving the company with ample cushion to maintain the dividend if earnings temporarily decline, while still retaining capital for growth.</p>
    <p>A payout ratio above 100% means the company is paying out more than it earns, which is unsustainable in the long run.</p>

    <p>To further understand how valuation metrics impact stock prices and dividend sustainability, consider reading our deep dive on the <a href="/what-is-pe-ratio">P/E Ratio</a>. If you plan on holding dividend-paying Canadian stocks, maximizing your <a href="/what-is-tfsa">TFSA</a> contribution room is crucial to avoid taxes on your passive income.</p>

    <div class="card FAQ">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <details>
        <summary>How is dividend yield calculated?</summary>
        <p>Dividend yield is calculated by dividing the annual dividend per share by the current share price, then multiplying by 100 to get a percentage.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>What is a dividend yield trap?</summary>
        <p>A dividend trap occurs when a company's dividend yield appears artificially high because its stock price has plummeted due to underlying financial problems, often leading to an eventual dividend cut.</p>
      </details>
      <details>
        <summary>Is a higher dividend yield always better?</summary>
        <p>No. Extremely high yields often indicate market skepticism that the dividend is sustainable. A moderate, growing dividend is generally safer than an exceptionally high, stagnant one.</p>
      </details>
    </div>
  </div>

